Testing by MyBroadband revealed that cereal boxes give an exaggerated perception of the amount of cereal in the box but that you do get what you pay for. The size of cereal boxes is a widely discussed topic, with some arguing that oversized packaging creates the illusion that it contains more product. Others believe the empty space in cereal boxes is used to protect the food product inside from damage. MyBroadband looked at the empty space of four popular kinds of cereal to assess how much breakfast food there was in each box. For this experiment, we tested the following cereal boxes: Most of the cereals surpassed the claimed weight on the boxes by a fair margin, while the Coco Pops were precisely correct at 350g. Due to their rectangular shape, it was easy to measure the boxes and calculate their volumes. The Rice Krispies box was the largest at almost 7 litres. The Coco Pops box was the smallest at just over 3.2 litres. To measure the empty space, we emptied the cereal bags into their respective boxes and measured the height from the top of each box. This test provided us with a measure of how much of the box was filled with the product. The best performer was Kelloggâ€™s Corn Flakes, which filled up 58% of the box. Bokomo Bran flakes were a close second at 55%. The Coco Pops and Rice Krispies did not fare as well, filling up only 39% and 36% of their respective boxes. The table below provides an overview of the weight of the cereal in each box. It also shows how much the product fills the package it comes in as a percentage. <img class="aligncenter wp-image-446340" src="https://mybroadband.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/All.jpg" alt="" width="640" height="854" srcset="https://mybroadband.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/All.jpg 800w, https://mybroadband.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/All-300x400.jpg 300w, https://mybroadband.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/All-400x533.jpg 400w, https://mybroadband.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/All